State MSM Profile: Kansas

Background & Methods

In 2015-2016, researchers at Emory University partnered with colleagues at the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) to develop methods to estimate the number of men who have sex with men (MSM) residing in each county in the United States. Using population and housing data from the American Community Survey and estimates from two peer-reviewed publications (Oster et al., 2015 & Purcell et al., 2012), they derived an indirect estimate of MSM population sizes that took into account both the urbanicity of the county as well as its density of households with a male householder and a male same-sex partner.

The full methodology is published in the Journal of Medical Internet Research - Public Health and Surveillance:

Grey JA, Bernstein KT, Sullivan PS, Purcell DW, Chesson HW, Gift TL, Rosenberg ES. Estimating the population sizes of men who have sex with men in US states and counties using data from the American Community Survey. JMIR Public Health Surveill 2016;2(1):e14. DOI: 10.2196/publichealth.5365

Overview of MSM in Kansas

An estimated 22,899 men who have sex with men (MSM) resided in Kansas in 2013, representing 0.5% of the 4,503,084 MSM in the United States. Of the 1,054,271 adult men of Kansas, 2.2% had had sex with another man in the past 5 years, which was less than the overall percentage of adult men in the United States who were MSM (3.9%).

Most MSM in Kansas resided in fringe counties of large metropolitan areas (47.5%). Including both central and fringe counties, 47.5% resided in a large metropolitan area.


Percentage of MSM by urbanicity, United States and Kansas, 2013

MSM in Kansas Counties

Among counties or county-equivalent areas in Kansas, Johnson County had the largest population of MSM at 7,487, representing 32.7% of all MSM in the state. Greeley County had the highest percentage of MSM among adult men in Kansas at 10.0%. This was greater than the percentage for Kansas as a whole, which was 2.2% of adult men.

Note: Range cutpoints for the map are based on the distribution of MSM among all counties in the United States.



MSM in Kansas Metropolitan Statistical Areas

Kansas City Metropolitan Statistical Area

The Kansas City MSA overlaps two states: Kansas and Missouri. The Kansas portion of the MSA had the largest metropolitan population of MSM in Kansas at 10,889, or 47.6% of all MSM in the state and 33.3% of the 32,669 MSM in the MSA. Of the 298,527 adult men in the Kansas part of Kansas City, an estimated 3.6% were MSM. This was less than the percentage of MSM among adult men in the MSA as a whole, which was 4.5% of adult men (32,669 out of 729,380).



Note: Range cutpoints for the map are based on the distribution of MSM among all counties in the United States.




Wichita Metropolitan Statistical Area

The Wichita MSA had a population of 4,184 MSM, or 18.3% of all MSM in Kansas. Of the 227,112 adult men in Wichita, an estimated 1.8% were MSM.

Note: Range cutpoints for the map are based on the distribution of MSM among all counties in the United States.




Topeka Metropolitan Statistical Area

The Topeka MSA had a population of 1,265 MSM, or 5.5% of all MSM in Kansas. Of the 84,638 adult men in Topeka, an estimated 1.5% were MSM.

Note: Range cutpoints for the map are based on the distribution of MSM among all counties in the United States.




Lawrence Metropolitan Statistical Area

The Lawrence MSA had a population of 870 MSM, or 3.8% of all MSM in Kansas. Of the 45,206 adult men in Lawrence, an estimated 1.9% were MSM.

Note: Range cutpoints for the map are based on the distribution of MSM among all counties in the United States.




Manhattan Metropolitan Statistical Area

The Manhattan MSA had a population of 590 MSM, or 2.6% of all MSM in Kansas. Of the 39,278 adult men in Manhattan, an estimated 1.5% were MSM.

Note: Range cutpoints for the map are based on the distribution of MSM among all counties in the United States.




St.Joseph Metropolitan Statistical Area

The St.Joseph MSA overlaps two states: Kansas and Missouri. The Kansas portion of the MSA had 51 MSM, or 0.2% of all MSM in the state and 3.9% of the 1,301 MSM in the MSA. Of 3,114 adult men in the Kansas part of St.Joseph, 1.6% were MSM. This was less than the overall percentage of MSM among adult men in the MSA, which was 2.6% of adult men (1,301 out of 50,439).

Note: Range cutpoints for the map are based on the distribution of MSM among all counties in the United States.
